{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487549"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:14:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:14:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"388"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/388"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.49,0.39,0.03,0.09,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"388"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86573"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/388"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"388"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70855"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"373"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"6292"},{"type":"tags","id":"6352"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"457"},{"type":"contributions","id":"521"},{"type":"contributions","id":"553"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28399"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86573"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man is brought into hospital following a head-on motor vehicle accident in which he was the driver. He complains of left lower leg pain. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination of the left leg, there is a deformity of the distal leg, with the overlying skin bruised but intact. There is tenderness to palpation over the distal lateral aspect of his leg. He is able to plantarflex his ankle without significant pain. Capillary refill in his great toe is four seconds and it is cool to touch. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA plain X-ray of the left lower limb shows a fracture of the fibula above the syndesmosis with an associated ankle dislocation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anatomical reduction","Orthopaedic review","Back slab","Fasciotomy","Spinal block"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhilst this man will certainly require an \u003Cstrong\u003Eorthopaedic assessment\u003C/strong\u003E of his bony injury, the immediate problem is one of impaired blood supply to his foot. The mechanism of decreased blood flow will be mechanical arterial obstruction as result of the dislocation. The most appropriate way of dealing with this is to reduce the fracture and try to \u003Cstrong\u003Ere-establish normal anatomical alignment\u003C/strong\u003E. Once realignment is confirmed with perfusion and pulse check, the fracture would require some form of splinting to improve arterial flow and reduce swelling. A \u003Cstrong\u003Ebackslab\u003C/strong\u003E applied longitudinally is the simplest and safest form of plaster splint providing less risk of constriction. \u003Cstrong\u003EFasciotomy\u003C/strong\u003E, a treatment for compartment syndrome, is not required as this is not a presentation of that condition. Compartment syndrome is characterised by immense pain due to tissue ischaemia due to microvascular compression and will not be associated with impaired pulse or capillary refill until very late in the course where irreversible muscle injury will have already occurred. \u003Cstrong\u003ESpinal blocks\u003C/strong\u003E are useful for definitive management of fractures and dislocations in the operating theatre.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Always assess neurovascular status in a suspected orthopaedic injury.","First step in neurovascular compromise secondary to a fracture is attempted anatomical reduction followed by re-checking the neurovascular status."],"references":["Pharaon SK, Schoch S, Marchand L, Mirza A, Mayberry J. Orthopaedic traumatology: fundamental principles and current controversies for the acute care surgeon. Trauma Surg Acute Care Open. 2018 Jan 8;3(1):e000117. doi: 10.1136/tsaco-2017-000117. PMID: 29766123; PMCID: PMC5887772. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29766123/","Parvizi J. Vascular injury and orthopaedics. Arthroplast Today. 2018 Nov 20;4(4):399-400. doi: 10.1016/j.artd.2018.10.005. PMID: 30569004; PMCID: PMC6287961. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6287961/","Altizer L. Neurovascular assessment. Orthop Nurs. 2002 Jul-Aug;21(4):48-50. doi: 10.1097/00006416-200207000-00008. PMID: 12224186. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12224186/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70855"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"388"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70855"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-22T14:54:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-22T14:57:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"388"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86573"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1